data.content:
Here's a complete migration analysis and rewrite.

## Critical Issues in .NET 8

| Issue | Impact |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed in .NET 5+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | **Won't wake `WaitOne()` on .NET Core** — behavioral change from Framework |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + lock | Race condition: rapid enqueues can orphan items (signal lost between `WaitOne`/`Reset`) |
| No cancellation | No clean shutdown path; `while(true)` runs forever |

## Migrated Code — Using `Channel<T>`

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>(
        new UnboundedChannelOptions { SingleReader = true });
    private Task? _processingTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();

        if (_cts is not null)
        {
            // If processing doesn't finish in time, cancel it
            var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
            using var delayCts = new CancellationTokenSource(effectiveTimeout);
            try
            {
                if (_processingTask is not null)
                    await _processingTask.WaitAsync(delayCts.Token);
            }
            catch (TimeoutException)
            {
                await _cts.CancelAsync();  // .NET 8 API — non-blocking cancel
                if (_processingTask is not null)
                    await _processingTask.ConfigureAwait(ConfigureAwaitOptions.SuppressThrowing);
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Migration Pitfalls

**1. `Thread.Abort()` is gone — no replacement.** Cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken` is the only path. Redesign loops to check tokens.

**2. `Thread.Interrupt()` behavior changed.** On .NET Framework it wakes `WaitOne()`; on .NET Core it silently does nothing for kernel waits. Your `Stop()` would hang, then throw on `Abort()`.

**3. The original has a lost-signal race.** Two rapid `Enqueue` calls: first `Set()` wakes the thread, second `Set()` is a no-op (already set), thread calls `Reset()` and processes one item, second item stays queued with no signal. `Channel<T>` eliminates this entirely.

**4. `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` vs `CancelAsync()`.** .NET 8 added `CancelAsync()` which doesn't invoke callbacks synchronously on the calling thread — prefer it to avoid deadlocks.

**5. If `Handle()` is async**, change the signature to `async Task HandleAsync(string item)` and await it directly — no need for `Task.Run` wrapping.
